{"mode":"human","topic":"How to manage and dealing with fake content on social media.", "opinion":"In my 61 years of life, I've had my fair share of navigating the murky waters of social media, and I've found myself increasingly entangled in the web of fabricated content. As a 61-year-old retail worker from Bologna, immersed in the daily grind of my profession, I've always relied on my keen eye for detail and my creative spirit to filter through the noise of online interactions. However, with social media becoming an integral part of our lives, the challenge of discerning fact from fiction has become a pressing concern, especially given my background and inherent personality traits.  Here's how I approach this daunting task: First, I've cultivated a healthy dose of skepticism. When encountering a post that seems too good (or bad) to be true, I pause and take a moment to question its authenticity. This doesn't mean I'll dismiss everything outright but rather approach each piece with a critical lens. For instance, if a post boasts extraordinary achievements or offers unrealistic promises, I'll look for corroboration from multiple sources. My education level, while primary school, has honed my ability to appreciate nuanced information and recognize when something seems overly simplistic or exaggerated.  Furthermore, I've found solace in my hobbies, particularly photography and rock climbing. These activities have sharpened my observational skills and taught me to appreciate the subtleties of reality, making it easier to spot discrepancies in online content. My low levels of extraversion and neuroticism might make me less inclined to engage in heated debates or react impulsively to sensationalized claims, but they've also endowed me with a calming introspection that allows me to analyze information more objectively.  My atheist beliefs lean towards moderate agreeableness, which means I'm generally open to different perspectives, yet I remain firm in my own convictions. 